AGI - Over half of primary school children and girls are convinced that in man and woman life they have distinct social roles: the first of power and command, the second of care and care (medium-high adherence to the male stereotyped role, 58.6%; female, 52.9%). Among the Italian adolescents, and therefore to the increase of age and exposure to extra-family secondary socialization environments, the sexist ideas inoculated by gender stereotypes are weakened only, in particular among girls (average-high adherence to the male stereotypical role, 28.3%; female, 30.8%).
These are the data collected by the Group of Social Changes, Evaluation and Methods (MUSA) of the Institute of Population Research and Social Policy of the National Research Council (Cnr-Irpps), which produced a Guide: Gender stereotypes to teach young people, parents and teachers to deconstruct them.
To simple questions, such as: What's a stereotype? 'What are the gender roles?', 'How do we hire them?', 'What do you feed?', 'What effects?', 'When you lower them?', correspond short and clear answers, elaborated by experts. The 'Guida', explains Antonio Tintori, researcher Cnr-Irpps and coordinator of the MUSA team, was born to satisfy the requests arrived from many schools of every order and degree of Italy: having an extra tool to raise awareness and educate the new generations to overcome stereotypes that, even in a subdued way, can condition the life choices of children and adolescents. "Many Italian teenagers explicitly approve violence and discrimination: 2 out of 10 declare openly homophobic and 1 out of 10 are racist and sexist," explains Antonio Tintori.&nbsp;
"In addition, about 3 out of 10 are unable to recognize as violent acts such as insults, constraints, threats, as well as how they fail to recognize a stereotype of gender, which is the main form of social conditioning that we 'contrary' in the early years of life, mainly in the family. This is, in fact, the primary place of reproduction of social inequalities, although adults, usually, are not even aware of being the first agents of transmission of such a powerful social conditioning, which is at the origin of the many asymmetries between man and woman in the private, family, labour, economic, and cause of violence".
Pointing on the little ones, with the positive complicity of parents and school teachers, is the way to go if we really want to grow tomorrow's adults with a critical spirit and free ability to analyze and judge. In fact, "Digital stereotypes reproduce by means of a 'traditional socialization', of distinct educational models for males and females; they feed on social symbols of widespread diffusion, which are seemingly harmless elements but in reality they determine the early rooting of the hormonal roles: the colors (pink and celestial), the games (arms and dolls), the false myths (the blue prince and the princess to save), the distinct sports (the football and dance). These symbols are spread everywhere, from language (excessive masculine) to cartoons, from media content to school textbooks, to games, to narratives", concludes Tintori.&nbsp;
